ansition' away from its labor-intensive model, facing downward pricing pressure on traditional services and concerns about margin compression due to AI-driven efficiencies.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"query_index\": 9,\n      \"summary\": \"Top Indian IT firms are heavily investing in AI. Wipro has committed $1 billion to train its entire workforce, and Infosys has launched its 'Topaz' AI suite. Simultaneously, a robust startup ecosystem is emerging, focused on 'sovereign AI'—building foundational models for India. Companies like Sarvam AI and Krutrim are developing LLMs trained on Indian languages. Key implementation trends include agentic AI for workflow automation, Generative AI for developer productivity, and computer vision for manufacturing.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"knowledge_base_insights\": \"The next five years represent a pivotal structural transformation for the Indian IT sector, moving beyond a simple technology upgrade to a fundamental reinvention of its core business model. For three decades, the industry thrived on labor arbitrage. AI directly challenges this foundation by automating routine tasks, creating deflationary pressure on legacy services like application maintenance. The key theme is a divergence: while traditional revenue streams are at risk, new, high-value opportunities in AI consulting, implementation, and specialized services are emerging with premium billing rates. The sector's success will be measured by its ability to rapidly shift its revenue mix towards these new areas. This transition is creating a 'capability arbitrage' model, where deep domain expertise and specialized AI skills are more valuable than a large workforce. Furthermore, the rise of 'Sovereign AI' initiatives and the evolution of Global Capability Centers (GCCs) into innovation hubs signify India's ambition to not just be a service provider but also a creator of core AI technologies. This period will be challenging, defined by the monumental task of reskilling millions, but